```c++
#include <iostream>
#include <fstream>
#include <string>
#include <vector>
using namespace std;
int countWord(string word, vector<string> fileLines) {
    int count = 0;
    for (string line : fileLines) {
        if (line.find(word) != string::npos) {
            count++;
        }
    }
    return count;
}
int main() {
    ifstream fin("input.txt");
    vector<string> fileLines(istream_iterator<string>(fin), istreambuf_iterator<char>());
    fin.close();
    string word = "example";
    int count = countWord(word, fileLines);
    cout << "The word \"" << word << "\" occurs " << count << " times in the file." << endl;
    return 0;
}
```
In this program, we first include the necessary header files and define a function `countWord` that takes in a string `word` and a vector of strings `fileLines` as parameters. The function counts the number of occurrences of the given word in the file by iterating over each line in the file and checking if the word is present in the line.
In the `main` function, we open the input file using an `ifstream` object, read the contents of the file into a vector of strings, and then call the `countWord` function to count the number of occurrences of the word "example" in the file. Finally, we print out the result.
Note that you can modify the program to count the occurrences of any word of your choice, simply by changing the value of the `word` variable in the `main` function.

